title: Effect of LY450139 a y-Secretase Inhibitor, on the Progression of Alzheimer's Disease as Compared With Placebo
description_brief:
Alzheimer's disease (AD) is a fatal degenerative disease of the brain for which there is no cure. AD causes brain cells to die. AD is thought to be caused by an excess of beta amyloid (β-amyloid), a sticky protein in the brain that forms amyloid plaques. At autopsy, AD patients are required to have these amyloid plaques in the brain in order to have a definitive diagnosis of AD. Inhibiting the enzyme gamma-secretase (γ-secretase) lowers the production of β-amyloid. Semagacestat (LY450139) is a functional γ-secretase inhibitor and was shown to lower β-amyloid in blood and spinal fluid in humans tested thus far and in blood, spinal fluid and brain in animals tested thus far. This study used several different tests to measure the effect of semagacestat on both β-amyloid and amyloid plaques for some patients. The buildup of amyloid plaques was measured by a brain scan that takes a picture of amyloid plaques in the brain. Other tests measured the overall function of the brain and brain size in some patients. In this trial, patients who initially received placebo (inactive sugar pill) were, at a certain point in the study, switched over to active drug, semagacestat. In other words, all patients could eventually receive active drug. Each patient's participation could last approximately 2 years. Patients taking approved AD medications were permitted to participate in this study and continue taking these medications during the study. All patients who completed this study had the option to continue receiving semagacestat by participating in an open label study.

Preliminary results from this study (LFBC) (and another similar study LFAN \[NCT00594568\]) showed semagacestat did not slow disease progression and was associated with worsening of clinical measures of cognition and the ability to perform activities of daily living. Study drug was stopped in all studies. LFBC, LFAN and open label LFBF (NCT01035138) have been amended to continue collecting safety data, including cognitive scores, for at least seven months. The CT-Registry will reflect results of analyses from the original protocol in addition to those from the amended protocol.

measures.title: Alzheimer's Disease Assessment Scale-Cognitive Subscale (ADAS-Cog11) Score (n=507, 533)
measures.description: The cognitive subscale of the ADAS (ADAS-Cog11) consists of 11 items assessing areas of function most typically impaired in AD: orientation, verbal memory, language, and praxis. The scale ranges from 0 to 70, with higher scores indicating greater disease severity.

measures.title: Alzheimer's Disease Cooperative Study Activities of Daily Living Inventory Score (n=505, 529)
measures.description: The Alzheimer's Disease Cooperative Study Activities of Daily Living (ADCS-ADL) Inventory Score is a 23-item inventory developed as a rater-administered questionnaire that should be answered by the participant's caregiver. The ADCS-ADL measures both basic and instrumental activities of daily living by participants. The total ADCS-ADL score ranges from 0 to 78, with lower scores indicating greater disease severity.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline in Alzheimer's Disease Assessment Scale- Cognitive Subscale (ADAS-Cog11) at 76 Weeks
outcomeMeasures.description: The cognitive subscale of the ADAS (ADAS Cog11) was used as a primary efficacy measure and consists of 11 items assessing areas of function most typically impaired in Alzheimer's disease (AD): orientation, verbal memory, language, and praxis. The scale ranges from 0 to 70, with higher scores indicating greater disease severity. Least Squares (LS) Mean value was controlled for baseline value, age, investigator, visit, and concomitant standard of care (SOC) medication.
outcomeMeasures.populationDescription: Intent to treat (ITT) population: All randomized participants who received at least 1 dose of study medication.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline in Clinical Dementia Rating Sum of Boxes (CDR-SB) at 76 Weeks
outcomeMeasures.description: CDR-SB is a semi-structured interview of participants and their caregivers. Participant's cognitive status is rated across 6 domains of functioning, including memory, orientation, judgment/problem solving, community affairs, home/hobbies, and personal care. Severity score assigned for each of 6 domains; total score (SB) ranges from 0 to 18. Higher scores indicate greater disease severity. Least Squares (LS) Mean value was controlled for baseline value, age, investigator, visit, and concomitant standard of care (SOC) medication.
outcomeMeasures.populationDescription: Intent to treat (ITT) population: All randomized participants who received at least 1 dose of study medication and had both baseline and post-baseline evaluable data.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline in the EuroQol 5-Dimensional Health-Related Quality of Life Scale Proxy Version (EQ-5D Proxy) Visual Analog Scale (VAS) at 76 Weeks
outcomeMeasures.description: EQ-5D (proxy version) measures mobility, self-care, usual activities, pain/discomfort, anxiety/depression; each has 3 severity levels (no, some, severe problems) coded to a 1-digit number (1-3). Digits are combined into 5-digit number describing health state. Numerals 1-3 are not added for total score. VAS assesses caregiver's impression of participant's overall health state; scores range: 0 to 100. Lower scores indicate greater disease severity. Least Squares (LS) Mean value controlled for baseline value, age, investigator, visit, and concomitant standard of care (SOC) medication.
outcomeMeasures.populationDescription: Intent to treat (ITT) population: All randomized participants who received at least 1 dose of study medication.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline in Quality of Life in Alzheimer's Disease (QoL-AD) at 76 Weeks
outcomeMeasures.description: Assess QoL for AD: participant rates mood, relationships, memory, finances, physical condition, and overall QoL assessment. Each of 13 items, rated on a 4-point scale. Sum of items=total score (range: 13 to 52). Higher scores indicate greater QoL. Participant's primary caregiver asked to complete same measure. Least Squares (LS) Mean value controlled for baseline value, age, investigator, visit, and concomitant standard of care (SOC) medication.
outcomeMeasures.populationDescription: Intent to treat (ITT) population: All randomized participants who received at least 1 dose of study medication.

groups.description: Participants received 60 mg LY450139 orally once daily for 2 weeks followed by 100 mg LY450139 orally once daily for 2 weeks, then 140 mg LY450139 orally once daily until Week 88.

groups.title: Placebo
groups.description: Participants received placebo orally once daily for the first 76 weeks. At the end of 76 weeks, participants in the placebo arm received LY450139 titrated up to 140 mg orally once daily until Week 88.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline in Alzheimer's Disease Assessment Scale (ADAS-Cog14) at 76 Weeks
outcomeMeasures.description: ADAS-Cog14 is ADAS-Cog11 augmented with delayed free recall, digit cancellation, and maze completion measures. A score of 0 to 10 for delayed free recall and a conversion code of 0 to 5 for digit cancellation and maze completion provide total score ranges for this extended ADAS-Cog14 of 0 to 90. Higher scores indicate greater disease severity. Least Squares (LS) Mean value was controlled for baseline value, age, investigator, visit, and concomitant standard of care (SOC) medication.

limitationsAndCaveats.description: All dosing for 4-week post-study drug cessation timeframe outcome measures stopped after protocol-specified interim review showed dose-dependent cognitive/functional worsening for LY450139 participants. No assessments made during 32-week follow up.

explanation_target: Reason: The investigational agent is semagacestat (LY450139), an oral small‑molecule inhibitor of γ‑secretase intended to reduce production of β‑amyloid (Aβ) and therefore target Alzheimer’s pathology (amyloid plaques) — i.e., a disease‑targeting mechanism rather than a symptomatic cognitive enhancer or a psychiatric/symptom management treatment. citeturn0search4turn0search0

Act: Key trial details extracted from the description and registries — drug name: semagacestat (LY450139); drug type: γ‑secretase inhibitor, oral small molecule; comparator: placebo with later switch/crossover to active and open‑label extension; primary intent: disease modification by lowering Aβ/amyloid burden. The Phase III studies were halted because semagacestat did not slow disease progression and was associated with worsened cognition and function, so dosing was stopped and safety follow‑up continued. citeturn0search6turn0search0turn0search4

Reflect: Classification check — semagacestat is a small‑molecule enzyme inhibitor directly aimed at an upstream pathological mechanism (amyloid production). That fits the definition of 'disease‑targeted small molecule'. Although the trial measured cognition and function, the mechanism is disease‑targeting (not purely symptomatic), and the observed worsening of cognition does not change the mechanism class. Sources: Eli Lilly press release and peer‑reviewed Phase III report (NEJM) and trial registry entries. citeturn0search0turn0search4turn0search5
explanation_agent: Reason: The investigational agent is semagacestat (LY450139), a small‑molecule inhibitor of γ‑secretase intended to reduce production of β‑amyloid (Aβ) from APP — directly targeting the amyloid production pathway and amyloid pathology. citeturn0search0turn0search3

Act: Extracted details — drug: semagacestat (LY450139); mechanism: oral γ‑secretase inhibitor that lowers Aβ synthesis in CNS; development: progressed to Phase III but dosing was halted because treated patients worsened compared with placebo. These facts support classification under the CADRO category for amyloid‑related interventions. citeturn0search1turn0search0turn0search2

Reflect: The mechanism is disease‑targeting (reducing Aβ generation), not a symptomatic or non‑therapeutic intervention, and no other dominant target (e.g., tau, inflammation) is described — therefore the most specific CADRO match is A) Amyloid beta. The negative clinical outcome (worse cognition) does not change the mechanistic classification. citeturn0search0turn0search5
